2D simulated case study: Diagnosis of the HSGP approximation

Gabriel Riutort-Mayol

2022-05-15.

This notebook implements the HSGP model fit and diagnosis on the 2D dataset in case study 5.3 ‘Simulated data for 2D and 3D functions’ in Riutort-Mayol, G., Bürkner, P. C., Andersen, M. R., Solin, A., & Vehtari, A. (2020; updated in 2022). Practical Hilbert space approximate Bayesian Gaussian processes for probabilistic programming. arXiv preprint arXiv:2004.11408.

2 Synthetic dataset

A synthetic dataset \(\boldsymbol{y}\) with a true data generating function \(f(\boldsymbol{x})\), with \(\boldsymbol{x}_i \in {\rm I\!R}^2\), where \(f(\boldsymbol{x})\) is a Gaussian process (GP) with a squared exponential kernel. Gaussian errors \(\boldsymbol{\epsilon}\) are added to \(f(\boldsymbol{x})\) to form the final synthetic noisy dataset \(\boldsymbol{y}\).

\[\begin{align*} \begin{split} \boldsymbol{y} &= \boldsymbol{f} + \boldsymbol{\epsilon} \\ \boldsymbol{\epsilon} &\sim \text{Normal}(\boldsymbol{0}, \sigma^2 \boldsymbol{I}) \\ f(\boldsymbol{x}) &\sim \text{GP}(0, k(\boldsymbol{x}, \boldsymbol{x}', \theta)), \end{split} \end{align*}\]

where \(k(\boldsymbol{x}, \boldsymbol{x}', \theta)\) is a squared exponential kernel as a function of input values \(\boldsymbol{x}\) and parameters \(\theta=(\alpha,\boldsymbol{\ell})\), where \(\alpha\) is the marginal variance of the GP function and \(\boldsymbol{\ell}=(\ell_1,\ell_2)\) the lengthscale of the kernel for dimensions 1 and 2, respectively.

4 Functional relationships among \(m\), \(\ell\) and \(c\) parameters in the HSGP approach

Relationship among the number of basis functions \(m\), the lengthscale \(\ell\) and the boundary factor \(c\) for a squared exponential kernel in the HSGP approach:

\[\begin{align*} m= 1.75 \frac{c}{\frac{\ell}{S}} \;\; \Leftrightarrow \;\; \frac{\ell}{S}= 1.75 \, \frac{c}{m} \tag{4.1} \end{align*}\]

m_QE <- function(c,l,S) ceiling(1.75 * c / (l/S))
l_QE <- function(c,m,S) round(S * 1.75 * c / m, 3)

with

\[\begin{align*} c \, \geq \, 3.2 \, \frac{\ell}{S}\;\; \& \;\;c \, \geq \frac{1}{2} \tag{4.2} \end{align*}\]

as a function of \(\ell\) and \(S\), where \(S\) is the half range of the input domain

c_vs_l_QE <- function(l,S){
    c =  3.2*l/S
    if(c < 1.2)
      c = 1.2
  c
}

5 Lengthscale diagnostic

The HSGP lengthscale diagnostic is defined as:

\[\begin{align*} \hat{\ell} + 0.01 \geq \ell \tag{5.1} \end{align*}\]

diagnostic <- function(l,l_hat) l_hat + 0.01 >= l

6.1.1 Setting \(m\), \(\ell\) and \(c\)

If iteration \(i=1\):

  1. Making a first guess for lengthscale \(\ell_i\)

  2. The boundary factor \(c_i\) has to fulfill equation (4.2)

  3. The number of basis functions \(m_i\) has to fulfill equation (4.1)

if(i==1){
  l1[i] <- 0.5
  c1[i] <- c_vs_l_QE(l=l1[i], S=S1)
  m1[i] <- m_QE(c=c1[i], l=l1[i], S=S1)
  
  l2[i] <- 1
  c2[i] <- c_vs_l_QE(l=l2[i], S=S2)
  m2[i] <- m_QE(c=c2[i], l=l2[i], S=S2)
}

6.1.2 Matrix of \(D\)-tuples

Matrix of \(D\)-tuples as in equation (10) in the paper

indices <- matrix(NA, m1[i]*m2[i], D)
mm=0;
for (r in 1:m1[i]){
    for (s in 1:m2[i]){
        mm = mm+1
        indices[mm,] = c(r, s)
    }
}

6.1.5 Model evaluation

Root mean square error rmse, Bayesian \(R^2\) (Coefficient of determination) eR, and expected log predictive density elpd.

noise <- as.matrix(fit[[i]], pars = c("noise"))

# elpd
elpd[i] <- round(median(summary(fit[[i]], pars = c("elpd"))$summary[,1]), 2)

6.1.6 Diagnosis

Lengthscale estimate \(\hat{\ell}_i\) in the HSGP approximation

l_hat1[i] <- round(summary(fit[[i]], pars = "lscale[1]", probs = c(0.05, 0.95))$summary[,1], 2)
l_hat2[i] <- round(summary(fit[[i]], pars = "lscale[2]", probs = c(0.05, 0.95))$summary[,1], 2)

Check the diagnostic of whether \(\, \hat{\ell}_i + 0.01 \geq \ell_i\) (5.1)

check1[i] <- diagnostic(l1[i], l_hat1[i])
check2[i] <- diagnostic(l2[i], l_hat2[i])

Summary table of diagnosis

  • rmse_gp refers to the root mean square error of the HSGP function with the GP function as the reference.

  • rmse refers to the root mean square error of the HSGP function with the true function as the reference.

6.2.1 Setting \(m\), \(\ell\) and \(c\)

If the diagnostic \(\hat{\ell}_{i-1} + 0.01 \geq \ell_{i-1}\) (5.1) is TRUE and iteration \(i=2\):

  1. Update \(m_i = m_{i-1} + 2\)

  2. The boundary factor \(c_i\) has to fulfill (4.2) where \(c(\cdot)\) is evaluated as a function of \(\hat{\ell}_{i-1}\)

  3. The lengthscale \(\ell_i\) has to fulfill (4.1)

if(diagnostic(l1[i-1], l_hat1[i-1]) & i==2){
  m1[i] <- m1[i-1] + 2
  c1[i] <- c_vs_l_QE(l=l_hat1[i-1], S=S1)
  l1[i] <- l_QE(c=c1[i], m=m1[i], S=S1)
}

if(diagnostic(l2[i-1], l_hat2[i-1]) & i==2){
  m2[i] <- m2[i-1] + 2
  c2[i] <- c_vs_l_QE(l=l_hat2[i-1], S=S2)
  l2[i] <- l_QE(c=c2[i], m=m2[i], S=S2)
}

If the diagnostic \(\hat{\ell}_{i-1} + 0.01 \geq \ell_{i-1}\) (5.1) is FALSE:

  1. Update \(\ell_i = \hat{\ell}_{i-1}\)

  2. The boundary factor \(c_i\) has to fulfill (4.2)

  3. The number of basis functions \(m_i\) as a function of \(\ell_i\) and \(c_i\) by using (4.1)

if(!diagnostic(l1[i-1], l_hat1[i-1])){
  l1[i] <- l_hat1[i-1]
  c1[i] <- c_vs_l_QE(l=l1[i], S=S1)
  m1[i] <- m_QE(c=c1[i], l=l1[i], S=S1)
}

if(!diagnostic(l2[i-1], l_hat2[i-1])){
  l2[i] <- l_hat2[i-1]
  c2[i] <- c_vs_l_QE(l=l2[i], S=S2)
  m2[i] <- m_QE(c=c2[i], l=l2[i], S=S2)
}

6.3.5 Model evaluation

eR[i] <- round(median(sd_f^2/(sd_f^2 + noise^2)), 2)

# elpd
elpd[i] <- round(median(summary(fit[[i]], pars = c("elpd"))$summary[,1]), 2)
